orth, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Chelsworth, Suffolk, England":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1255–":"circa 1255–Overleden","1205–1278":"1205–1278","1255–Female":"1255–Overleden","1250–1284":"1250–1284","1275–Male":"1275–Overleden","1276–1298":"1276–1298","1230–1278":"1230–1278","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","25 June 1275":"25 juni 1275","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1205":"1205","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1298":"1298","1276":"1276","about 1255":"circa 1255","about 1276":"circa 1276","Chelsworth, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chelsworth, Suffolk, England":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1255–":"about 1255–Deceased","1205–1278":"1205–1278","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1250–1284":"1250–1284","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1276–1298":"1276–1298","1230–1278":"1230–1278","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","25 June 1275":"25 June 1275","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1205":"1205","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1298":"1298","1276":"1276","about 1255":"about 1255","about 1276":"about 1276","Chelsworth, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Chelsworth, Suffolk, England":"Chelsworth, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hastings","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan de Hastings was born about 1255, in Eaton Hastings, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir William de Hastings. She married Bennet de Blakenham in 1271, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1255–":"umbes 1255–Surnud","1205–1278":"1205–1278","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1250–1284":"1250–1284","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1276–1298":"1276–1298","1230–1278":"1230–1278","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1284":